My research interest lies in neural recording technologies and biological plasticity. Building on work in neural frontend circuit design and theoretical neuroscience, I am applying to the Research Associates Program for the opportunity to study how neural circuits are assembled and calibrated during development, under the mentorship of the Schoppik Lab.

My master's thesis with Dr. Jabeom Koo at Cooper Union designs recording hardware that must resolve microvolt-scale brain signals within extreme power budgets. My independent research with Dr. Stanislav Mintchev takes the opposite approach: I study when standard mean-field reductions of spiking networks fail once plasticity is involved---how learning welds synaptic weights and spike statistics into a closed loop that reduced models cannot track, causing them to drift to incorrect equilibria or miss dynamics the full network produces. Working on both problems has convinced me that theory should drive hardware design. If plasticity continuously reconfigures individual neurons while preserving population-level structure, then recording systems should be designed to capture that structure.

At NYU Langone's Long Lab, I built the computational pipeline for analyzing vocalizations and began developing an automated system for minimally supervised experiments. One idea from the lab that reshaped my thinking was that sleep replay can reveal a circuit's intrinsic architecture---that when external input is removed, the circuit still runs its learned sequence, exposing connectivity that is invisible during normal behavior. For me, it connected theory to biology: here was a way to observe what plasticity builds inside a living circuit. It made me want to understand how that architecture is assembled during development.

The Schoppik Lab addresses this directly. Reading the lab's recent work reframed how I think about development and plasticity. Leary et al. (2025) showed that the VOR circuit matures entirely without sensory experience, its development rate-limited not by the brain but by the neuromuscular junction. I find the natural follow-up question compelling: if this circuit calibrates itself from within, when does experience-dependent plasticity take over, and what is it for? I want to contribute to this work, from developing experimental apparatus like the tilt-delivery platform to participating in the imaging and electrophysiology experiments themselves.

My long-term goal is a PhD bridging circuit design and developmental neuroscience---building recording systems informed by how real circuits learn. The Research Associates Program would provide the foundation for that trajectory. My time in the Long Lab showed me what NYU Langone's neuroscience community looks like up close: lab members who took me behind the curtain of a two-photon microscope to walk me through the entire laser setup, and who offered their personal support on my applications. I had studied two-photon imaging in my Medical Imaging course, but seeing the system firsthand felt entirely different---it made clear how much I stand to gain from immersing myself in this community. I am eager to do so in the Schoppik Lab.
